        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New York</placeName> <date>May 4. 5609</date>.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee> <add>Hebrew</add></p>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
		<pb n="3"/>
			<p><add>Hebrew</add></p> 
          <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>N. Y.</placeName> <date>May 4&#44; 1849</date>.</p>
			<p>To my friend and beloved&#44; <addressee>I liezar&#44; Rev.</addressee><lb/> <addressee>Isaac Leeser</addressee>&#58; Please do not be angry<lb/> that I have delayed until today to<lb/> answer your letter that I received the<lb/> exchange. For at that time I had a pain in<lb/> my eyes and I could not write. I asked<lb/> <persName>Dr. Merzbacher</persName> to let you know that I<lb/> received the exchange and then I waited<lb/> expediently for the answer of the man who<lb/> owns the Sefer Torah. He&#44; too&#44; answered me<lb/> asking that I send it to him. I did not<lb/> want to write to you and let you know<lb/> of this&#44; for everyday I expected to re&#45;<lb/>ceive it and could not understand why he delayed. Finally the man<lb/> came here this past week and told<lb/> me that he does not want to send<lb/> it in view of the fact that I know the<lb/> Sefer Torah. Unless I desire to take it<lb/> and pay &#36;100 for it along with the ark.<lb/> Seeing that he could not be trusted&#44; I</p>
		<pb n="4"/>
			<p>was very sorry to have been unable<lb/> to fulfill your request and&#44; more so&#44;<lb/> that I delayed the matter till now.<lb/> Then God intervened and&#44; by a good coin&#45;<lb/>cidence&#44; a man arrived here and brought<lb/> this very Sefer Torah but did not want to<lb/> give it to me on commission. I took it and<lb/> paid for it with cash&#59; since I like it so<lb/> much both from the point of view of the<lb/> writing and from the parchment. For<lb/> I can safely say there is no such writing<lb/> in the entire land. Therefore&#44; if you<lb/> want it for &#36;90. please let me know&#44;<lb/> and if not&#44; be good enough to<lb/> return it to me at once&#44; for I have<lb/> another customer for it who will<lb/> probably arrive next week.</p>
			<p>If you want to give me some<lb/> books on commission&#44; both Hebrew and<lb/> English&#44; especially prayer books and<lb/> Pentateuchs&#44; as cheaply as possible&#44; I should</p>
		<pb n="5"/>
			<p>be pleased. Perhaps I shall be able to<lb/> earn something. The first part of the<lb/> Torah being written by <persName>Mr. Ettinger</persName>&#44; the scribe&#44;<lb/> will be looked over by me on <date>Sunday</date> next&#44;<lb/> since this time I have more leisure. Please<lb/> let me know whether the article written in Eng&#45;<lb/>lish about the meeting which took place in<lb/> <date>June</date> and which is signed by you&#44; was sent<lb/> to my address&#44; or don&#39;t you know anything<lb/> about it&#63; I have to make it short be&#45;<lb/>cause of a wedding which is to take place in<lb/> my house&#44; although I have more to say.</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)">Your friend&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(9)"><persName role="author">Schneor Nusbaum</persName></p>

          
        </body>
